            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              Well I think its great the Navy is upgrading and it is cool tech am I the only one that thinks maybe we shouldn't have an entire warship controllable from a computer that is networked (wirelessly at that). I'm all for robotics and AI but I don't think we are at the stage where we should be putting massive weapon systems under complete computer control. I'm sure the Navy has thought of this and has multiple safe guards in place to prevent it but what stops 1 person from taking over if all the control units are interchangeable? <br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25507683#p25507683" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">thekaj</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Perhaps it's appropriate that the first commanding officer of the Zumwalt will be Captain James Kirk (yes, that's actually his name).</div><br />This <span style="font-style: italic">can't</span> be a coincidence.  Somewhere, some admiral was looking at crew manifests, saw some &quot;Petty Officer 3rd Class James Kirk&quot;, and decided &quot;oh we can't let this go to waste.&quot;</div><br />They should have saved him for when the enterprise name gets reused.

              

              
              
