          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25508057#p25508057" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Nijyo</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">This sounds pretty neat and all, but did anyone else start thinking of this baby about half-way through the technical descriptions?:<br /><br /><img src="http://images4.wikia.nocookie.net/__cb20090606201619/memoryalpha/en/images/9/9b/USS_Excelsior_stalls_outside_Spacedock.jpg" alt="Image" /></div><br /><br />Oh, I thought of starships as soon as I saw the CO's name. Minor nitpick: that's USS Excelsior, which in Trek lore is an experimental ship (notice the NX registry -- X denotes an experimental design just as in the modern Navy) and the first of her class. A ship of that design was later named Enterprise and appeared in a later movie (Generations) -- that shot is from Star Trek III. The Enterprise did not have the experimental propulsion system that Excelsior had -- it turned out to be impractical and the complexity wasn't worth the benefit.<br /><br />It's not unlike how a 1/4 scale model of the tumblehome design was built to ascertain whether it would be seaworthy.<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sea_Jet">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sea_Jet</a><!-- m --><br /><br />From a distance, these ships don't look like what we'd expect ships to look like, since the design's been out of use for so long. The Sea Jet actually showed up on a cryptid website:<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.cryptomundo.com/cryptozoo-news/paddler-pic/">http://www.cryptomundo.com/cryptozoo-news/paddler-pic/</a><!-- m --> (lower right).

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
